CHILEAN DAYBOOK: Central Bank Outlook, Cesco Copper Conference

-- B y   N a t h a n   C r o o k s
-- 
2011-04-04T03:00:01Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-04-04/chilean-daybook-central-bank-outlook-cesco-copper-conference.html
Chile’s Central Bank President Jose De Gregorio will deliver the bank’s quarterly forecasts for
inflation, economic growth and copper prices.  WHAT TO WATCH:
*Central bank monetary policy report from 9:30 a.m. New York
time at the bank’s downtown Santiago offices.
*Mining and Energy Minister  Laurence Golborne  speaks at an
exploration seminar at Sheraton Hotel in Santiago as part of the
Cesco copper conference from 7:30 a.m. New York time.
*State-owned copper producer Codelco holds breakfast event.  ECONOMY:
*Chilean policy makers voted unanimously to raise the benchmark
interest rate by a half-point in March after inflation
expectations rose, according to the meeting minutes posted April
1 on the central bank website.  EQUITIES:
*The Ipsa index rose 1.9 percent to 4,712.85. Steelmaker Cap SA
rose 4.1 percent after its iron mining unit signed supply
contracts for a total 1.5 million metric tons a year starting
2013. Empresas Copec SA increased 1.6 percent to the highest
price in nine weeks after reporting full-year net income of a
record $1 billion, up from $576 million in 2009. Empresas La
Polar SA rose 7.5 percent on speculation of the sale of a stake.  MARKETS:
* Chile ’s peso posted a second weekly gain after breaching its
previous trading range as mining companies bought pesos. The
currency gained 0.3 percent on April 1 to a three-week high of
475.85 per  U.S. dollar . It strengthened 0.7 percent last week.
*Foreign investors in the forwards market trimmed bets against
the peso to $2.1 billion on March 30, the lowest since March 14,
according to the latest central bank data.
*The yield on Chilean 10-year bonds in pesos rose 5 basis
points, or 0.05 percentage point, to 6.45 percent. The spread
between five-year and 10-year central bank bonds fell to zero
yesterday as both bonds yielded 6.4 percent, according to data
compiled by Bloomberg.
*Copper, Chile’s largest export, fell 4.9 cents, or 1.1 percent,
to close at $4.2585 a pound on the Comex in  New York . The price
rose to a record $4.6575 a pound on Feb. 15 amid a growing
shortage of the industrial metal.  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
